{{Infobox Software | name = Mnemosyne | logo = Mnemosyne 1.x logo.png | developer = [[Peter Bienstman]] | released = February 8th, 2006 | latest release version = 2.6 | latest release date = {{release date and age|2017|12|11}} | programming language = [[Python (programming language)|Python]] | operating system = [[Windows]], [[Linux]], [[macOS]], [[Android OS|Android]] | size = 3.4&nbsp;MB | genre = Accelerated Learning & Memory Software | license = [[GNU Affero General Public License|AGPL v3]] (except sync client), [[GNU Lesser General Public License|LGPL v3]] (sync client) | website = {{URL|mnemosyne-proj.org}} }}
'''Mnemosyne''' (named for the Greek goddess of memory, [[Mnemosyne]]) is a line of [[spaced repetition]] software developed from 2003 until the present.
==Features== * Spacing algorithm based on an early version of the [[SuperMemo]] algorithm, SM-2,<ref>[http://www.supermemo.com/english/ol/sm2.htm SM-2] Optimization of learning, Master's Thesis, University of Technology in Poznan, 1990 and adapted for publishing as an independent article on the web. (P.A.Wozniak, May 10, 1998)</ref> with some modifications that deal with early and late repetitions.<ref>"[http://www.mnemosyne-proj.org/principles.php Principles]", The Mnemosyne Project, retrieved June 3rd, 2008</ref> * Supports [[Image|pictures]], [[sound]], [[video]], [[HTML]], Flash and [[LaTeX]] * Portable (can be installed on a [[USB stick]]) * Categorization of cards * Learning progress statistics * Stores learning data (represented as decks of cards that each have a question and an answer side) in ".mem" database files, which are interoperable with a number of other spaced repetition applications * Plugins and [[JavaScript]] support * Review cards on Android devices. * Synchronization between other machines
== Overview == Each day, the software displays each card that is scheduled for repetition. The user then grades their recollection of the card's answer on a scale of 0-5. The software then schedules the next repetition of the card in accordance with the user's rating of that particular card and the database of cards as a whole. This produces an active, rather than passive, review process.
==Software== Mnemosyne is written in [[Python (programming language)|Python]], which allows for its use on [[Microsoft Windows]], [[Linux]], and {{nowrap|[[Mac OS X]]}}. A client program for review on [[Android (operating system)|Android]] devices is also available but needs to be synchronized by the desktop program. Users of the software usually make their own database of cards, although pre-made Mnemosyne databases are available, and it is possible to import SuperMemo collections and text files. [[SQLite]] is used by the program to store files.
==Research== Mnemosyne collects data from volunteering users, and is a research project{{clarify|In what capacity? Associated with a university?|date=April 2017}} on [[long-term memory]].<ref>http://www.mnemosyne-proj.org/principles.php</ref>
An August 2009 version of the dataset was made available via [[BitTorrent (protocol)|BitTorrent]];<ref>[http://groups.google.com/group/mnemosyne-proj-users/browse_thread/thread/5f7ede5242badc9f Announcement]; [http://www.legittorrents.info/index.php?page=torrent-details&id=29b67f580ed97d6a10429697d5006c3eb47b2f18 torrent index]</ref> a January 2014 version is available for download.<ref>https://groups.google.com/d/msg/mnemosyne-proj-users/tPHlkTFVX_4/oF61BF44iQkJ</ref> Otherwise, the latest version is available from the author, Peter Bienstman, upon request.<ref>http://groups.google.com/group/mnemosyne-proj-users/browse_thread/thread/e00801ebb3bbfa72</ref>
