'''Nicasio Jiménez''' (born 12 March 1849,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.radiotrinidad.icrt.cu/Marzo|title=March|accessdate=27 January 2011|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110718163102/http://www.radiotrinidad.icrt.cu/Marzo|archivedate=18 July 2011|df=}}</ref> d. 1891) was a Cuban violin-cellist. He was the son of violinist [[Jose Julian Jiménez]] and brother of pianist and composer [[Lico Jiménez]]. His sisters Inés and Arcadia Jiménez were singers. His grandfather [[Francisco Nicasio Jiménez]] was an orchestra and band leader.<ref>{{cite book |title=Historia de la música cubana|author=Sanjurjo, Elena Pérez|year=1986}}</ref>
==Life== Nicasio Gregorio Jiménez was born in [[Trinidad, Cuba]], [[Las Villas (Cuba)|Las Villas]] province. Jiménez studied music as a child with his father and traveled to Germany with his father and brother in 1867<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ecured.cu/index.php/Jos%C3%A9_Manuel_Berroa|title=José Manuel Berroa|accessdate=27 January 2011}}</ref> to study music at the [[Leipzig]] Conservatory. He became noted as a cellist and took a position as Professor of Violincello at the Conservatory of [[Tours]].<ref>{{cite book |title=La Habana artística: Apuntes históricos|author=Ramírez, Serafín}}</ref>
With his father and brother, Nicasio formed one of the first all black ensembles, billed as "Das Negertrio",<ref>{{cite book |title=Routes of passage: rethinking the African diaspora: Volume 1, Part 1|author=Hamilton, Ruth Simms|year=2007}}</ref> and successfully toured in [[Europe]], the [[Americas]] and in [[Cuba]] as a soloist and with the ensemble, playing mostly 19th-century [[Romantic music|Romantic]] compositions.<ref>{{cite book |title=Das Negertrio Jimenez in Europe|author=Wright, Josephine|year=1981|publisher=The Black Perspective in Music, Foundation for Research in the Afro-American Creative Arts|jstor=1214195}}</ref>
