The '''Sabina School Park of Knowledge''' ({{lang-pt|Sabina Escola Parque do Conhecimento}}) is a [[science museum]] in [[Santo André]], [[São Paulo]], Brazil.<ref name="Sabina" /> Other planetaria in [[Greater São Paulo]] include [[Professor Aristóteles Orsini Planetarium]] and [[Carmo Planetarium]].

== History ==
The school was created by the Municipal Government of Santo André to provide scientific support to the municipal school network. Originally conceived in 2001, the construction of the building and the initial acquisition of the contents was completed in mid-2006. It was inaugurated on 11 February 2007. The building was designed by [[Paulo Mendes da Rocha]]. It is in an area of {{convert|24,000|sqm|sqft}}, with the building covering {{convert|14,000|sqm|sqft}}.<ref name="Sabina" />

== Main pavilion ==

The main pavilion covers {{convert|11,000|sqm|sqft}}.<ref name="Sabina" />

== Johannes Kepler Planetarium ==
The planetarium, named after [[Johannes Kepler]], is a {{convert|18|m|ft|abbr=on}}-diameter dome containing 247 seats and 13 wheelchair spaces. It uses a [[Carl Zeiss AG]] Starmaster SB to project over 6,000 stars, along with two digital projectors covering the entire dome.<ref name="planetarium" /> The planetarium and digital theatre covers {{convert|3,000|sqm|sqft}}.<ref name="Sabina" /> Shows last around 30 minutes. It is open to the public on weekends and holidays.<ref name="planetarium" />

